{
  "texts": [
    "Example-based explanations communicate why a model made a particular prediction via visual examples (Cai et al., 2019; Sui et al., 2021)-e.g., training images-as social science research has shown that humans can understand complex ideas using only examples (Renkl et al., 2009; Renkl, 2014).",
    "Influence estimation can assist in the selection of canonical training instances that are particularly important for a given class in general or a single test prediction specifically.",
    "Similarly, normative explanations-which collectively establish a \"standard\" for a given class (Cai et al., 2019) -can be selected from those training instances with the highest average influence on a held-out validation set.",
    "In cases where a test instance is misclassified, influence analysis can identify those training instances that most influenced the misprediction.",
    "Subsampling reduces the computational requirements of large datasets by training models using only a subset of the training data (Ting & Brochu, 2018)."
  ]
}